<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Hint on company tax rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government raised the prospect of a reduction in the rate of corporation
tax to 20 per cent for small companies yesterday, following its policy of
aligning the levy with the standard rate of income tax, David Owen writes.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, said such a move
might be possible, under questioning from Mr Chris Smith, a Labour
frontbench Treasury spokesman.
Mr Smith had asked for an indication of the government's future plans on
corporation tax, since it appeared to be its intention to expand the 20p
income tax band introduced in the last budget until it became effectively
the standard rate.
Mr Dorrell said the small-companies rate of 25 per cent reflected the
importance the government attached to ensuring a low marginal rate of tax
for wealth creation.
Mr Smith also used yesterday's Commons debate on the corporate tax-related
clauses of this year's finance bill to attack the government for its
'appalling' manufacturing investment record.
Proposing an amendment to lift first-year capital allowances to 40 per cent
from 25 per cent, he said the Tories had 'neglected and denigrated the
importance of manufacturing for far too long'.
The amendment was defeated with a government majority of 108 (339-231).
</TEXT>
