<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Criticisms of Cadbury report emerge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONCERNS about the recommendations of the Cadbury Committee's report on
corporate governance emerged yesterday in a survey published at a conference
sponsored by the Confederation of British Industry. The report was widely
hailed by the government and industry when it was published last month.
The heart of it was a voluntary code of practice for company directors,
accountants and auditors. Managements would have to defer more decisions to
non-executive directors and give shareholders more information.
Yesterday's conference in London heard that a survey of fund managers and
auditors by Burson-Marsteller, the public-relations company, found that a
majority of both groups felt the recommendations did not go far enough.
Most of the 22 leading fund managers and auditors interviewed felt that the
committee had been unwilling to produce a report that upset corporate
directors. One fund manager was quoted as saying: 'There are some things
they were not able to come out about as they would have liked.'
In particular, most shareholders doubted whether the voluntary nature of the
code would be effective. The survey found that the question of enforcement
was the most troubling to all respondents and the one that most divided
them. One fund manager was quoted as saying that while a voluntary approach
should be the initial one, 'if it becomes clear there isn't compliance, then
there should be legislation'.
The proposed means of enforcing compliance with the code is that to qualify
for a new Stock Exchange listing, companies will have to disclose the extent
to which they comply with the code, and where they do not, explain why.
Sir Andrew Hugh Smith, Stock Exchange chairman and a member of the Cadbury
Committee, speaking at the conference, defended that as an effective
enforcement mechanism. He said shareholders would be encouraged to take
managements to task for poor board structures, forcing companies to comply.
The survey found some institutional shareholder scepticism about that
approach. One shareholder said: 'There is no way of effective enforcement
other than delisting at the Stock Exchange. That would be like using a
nuclear weapon - in other words, it will never be used.'
Institutions are concerned that companies may not comply fully or accurately
with the new disclosure requirement and doubt whether the exchange would be
willing to put its full force behind enforcement, according to the survey.
Shareholders also said they wanted the committee's recommendations to
include that a company's lead bank be represented on its board in a
non-executive capacity. They also wanted recommendations that directors be
vetted prior to appointment, that there be still greater clarification of
the duties and responsibilities of directors, and that directors' service
contracts be no longer than three to six months.
Directors ousted for poor performance often leave with large redundancy
payments stemming from the company's obligation to pay them for the term of
their service contract. Company law allows directors to be appointed for up
to five years - longer if shareholders agree. The Cadbury Committee urges
that that be cut to three years - a period still too long for most fund
managers.
The survey quotes one fund manager as complaining that three years is too
long because 'there have been so many deadbeats kicked out of British
industry and taking huge cash handouts because of the service contracts and
it is one of the worst aspects of the way that companies are run'.
Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
