<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Boundaries of assisted areas are to be reviewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOUNDARIES of assisted areas are to be reviewed, prompting warnings that
the move may lead to a reduction in government financial assistance to the
regions.
A consultation paper, accompanying the announcement by Mr Tim Sainsbury, the
industry minister, said: 'It is unlikely that the coverage of the new map
will be greater than now, and it could be somewhat less.'
Specialists in regional policy noted yesterday that government financial
assistance had been steadily declining. They warned that a review of the
boundaries of assisted areas was likely to accentuate that trend.
The assisted areas map defines the geographical areas where, under regional
policy, industrial incentives can be paid to companies. There are two sorts
of assisted areas - development and intermediate - denoting the extent of
subsidies that can be paid. Such financial assistance cost Pounds 642.6m in
the 1986-87 financial year, but had declined to Pounds 264.4m by 1991-92.
During the 1980s, automatic entitlements to regional aid were phased out,
and subsidies have become discretionary on a project-by-project basis.
Assisted areas cover 35 per cent of the UK working population and, except
for parts of Cornwall and Devon, are concentrated north of a line drawn from
the Severn to the Wash. In its review of the areas to be included on a new
map, the government will take into account factors such as un-employment and
future economic performance.
Mr Keith Hayton, senior lecturer at Strathclyde University's centre for
planning, suggested that 'the core assisted areas' such as parts of
Scotland, north-east England, the Welsh valleys and the western tip of
Cornwall would remain on the map.
The government promised a review of the map during the present session of
parliament as far back as 1988, and European Community competition rules
mean that any changes will have to be negotiated with Brussels. The new map
should be published early next year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
