<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / Stoy and Finnie to merge: Accountancy firm will be 10th
largest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STOY HAYWARD, the UK's 11th-largest accountancy firm by fee income, is to
merge with Finnie &amp; Co, the 20th-largest.
The new firm - to be called Stoy Hayward - will have 176 partners and
directors, 1,300 professional staff and an annual fee income of more than
Pounds 82m, making it the 10th-largest firm under present rankings.
Mr Adrian Martin, managing partner at Stoy Hayward, said the merger was
agreed for strategic reasons and did not reflect any financial weaknesses in
either firm.
He said Stoy Hayward had been considering ways to strengthen its network in
the south-east since the mid 1980s as part of its expansion of its London
office. No professional staff and only a handful of support staff would lose
their jobs as a result, he said.
Mr Geoff Warren, senior partner of Finnie, will become the seventh member of
Stoy's management executive, and four of Finnie's partners will join the
seven Stoy partners on its partnership council, which sets general
principles for the firm.
He said Finnie's partners decided to begin looking for a merger partner late
last summer to strengthen the firm's presence outside the south-east and to
provide additional expertise in some practice areas.
Stoy Hayward was the only firm in which he was seriously interested, he
added.
Finnie's nine existing offices in the south-east will become Stoy Hayward
offices, 'in association with Finnie &amp; Co', while its central London head
office will move into Stoy's headquarters. Only its small branch in
Beverley, Humberside, will remain an independent firm.
No money will change hands as part of the deal, and negotiations over the
last few months have centred on how to structure profit-sharing between the
two sets of partners.
Profit-sharing will continue to reflect the different contributions of the
two firms until a new partnership remuneration agreement is redrafted in two
years.
Accountancy firms will be forbidden to audit the accounts of any companies
for which they have valued brands, pension funds, property and other assets,
under draft rules released yesterday by their professional bodies.
The change was widely welcomed in submissions from accountancy firms and
other bodies received in advance of the guidelines, issued by the chartered
accountants joint ethics committee, which represents the three institutes of
chartered accountants - in England and Wales, in Scotland and in Ireland.
They state that a firm should not audit any material specialist valuations
performed by the same firm or an associated practice, where the valuation
would be incorporated into the accounts as either the firm's or the
directors' valuation.
Among firms likely to be affected is Coopers &amp; Lybrand, which conducted
brand valuation for companies including Mirror Group Newspapers while acting
as auditors.
Another draft guideline issued yesterday states that firms should refuse to
give a second opinion on contentious accounting issues to a company audited
by another firm, unless they are in full possession of the information on
the subject held by the auditor.
The guidelines follow identification by the ethics committee of a number of
instances of 'opinion shopping', by which companies have undermined the
authority of their auditors by going elsewhere for a more sympathetic
ruling.
Specialist valuations; Opinion shopping; Predatory pricing. Comments and
copies available with SAE from Mr Jack Maurice, Secretary, CAJEC, 399
Silbury Blvd, Central Milton Keynes, MK9 2HL.
Accountancy column, Page 12
</TEXT>
