<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 92 / World Trade News: Brussels anger over US food export hitlist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission yesterday reacted angrily to the publication in
Washington of a Dollars 2bn EC food exports 'hit-list', half of which may
suffer punitive tariffs if the EC fails to reform its oilseeds subsidy
regime.
This latest escalation of the oilseeds row casts a pall over prospects of
concluding the Uruguay Round world trade liberalisation talks, in which the
US and EC can still not agree on how far each side should cut farm
subsidies.
The Dollars 2bn hit list, which ranges across wine, cheese, biscuits, gin,
liqueurs, tobacco, will be pared to Dollars 1bn after 30 days of being open
to public suggestions. It does not include whisky. This is a notional
estimate of damage caused by EC discrimination against the US's powerful
soyabean exporters. If imposed, the list would block about a quarter of EC
food exports to the US.
Brussels officials described the action as 'totally without justification
since it lacks any legal basis' within the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (Gatt) disputes procedures, now ostensibly being followed by both
sides. The EC has taken up a Gatt panel option to offer compensation to US
exporters while nevertheless challenging the Gatt ruling which it hopes
ultimately will be settled in the Uruguay Round.
Compensation would do nothing to answer US soya farmers' complaints.
'What is needed is fair access into the EC market so US soyabean farmers can
compete for the market. This can only be accomplished through reductions in
the EC oilseed subsidy programme,' said Mr Gary Riedel, president of the
American Soyabean Association, yesterday.
Mr Ray MacSharry, EC agriculture commissioner, said 'it would seem from this
action that the US is not interested in peace in international trade.'
The EC proposal over oilseeds will be put to the next meeting of the Gatt
Council on June 19. At the last Gatt Council meeting the EC blocked a report
from the dispute settlement panel which, for the second time, found that EC
policies impair the duty-free status accorded to soyabeans as a result of
previous negotiations.
By declaring its intention to press ahead with its hitlist against the EC
under Section 301 of the US Trade Act, the US is being attacked by Brussels
for flouting Gatt procedures by initiating unilateral sanctions. US
officials recognise this, but say the administration may press ahead
nevertheless. Senior EC officials believe the Bush administration is bowing
to the electoral pressures building up on the president, pointing out that
the sanctions list homes in on France and Ireland, two hardliners in the
farm subsidies row.
EC figures also show that US soya exporters have lost out mainly to lower
cost soya exporters like Argentina and Brazil, at a time when European
imports of soya have expanded significantly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
