<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Economic uncertainty leaves
equities lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
UNCERTAINTY among investors about the economic outlook and concern regarding
overvalued equity markets sent share prices into a brief tailspin yesterday,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 34.21 at 3,369.92.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 also ended lower, down 3.30 at
410.06, as did the Amex composite, down 3.37 at 393.06, and the Nasdaq
composite, down 8.21 at 573.80.
Turnover on the NYSE was 192m shares, and declines outpaced rises by a ratio
of more than two to one.
The market has moved little in the past three weeks, reflecting confusion
among investors about the short-term direction of share prices. Although
most recent economic data suggests that the recovery is advancing, albeit
very slowly, the pace of economic activity has been insufficient to generate
much fresh demand for equities.
Barring another interest rate cut, therefore, the market lacks strong
fundamental support, and it has become increasingly exposed to sudden
sell-offs spread across a range of cyclical and growth stocks.
Leading the way lower were classic cyclicals like Interna tional Paper, down
Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 64 7/8 , and Aluminum Company of America, down
Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 77 3/4 .
The former was not helped by a downgrade from analysts at the broking house,
Salomon Brothers, who cut their earnings estimates for several paper and
forest products companies to reflect pressures in the linerboard market.
Other stocks to suffer from the Salomon move were Georgia-Pacific, down
Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 60 7/8 , Temple Inland, Dollars 1 1/4 lower at
Dollars 47 5/8 , and Stone Container, Dollars 1 weaker at Dollars 22 5/8
At the same time, Salomon also downgraded its ratings of several newspaper
groups. Knight-Ridder fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 56 1/2 , Washington Post
gave up Dollars 3&gt; at Dollars 235 1/2 and Gannett slipped Dollars 2 3/8 to
Dollars 44 5/8 . In the same sector, Tribune Co dropped Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 40 5/8 after Smith Barney Harris Upham reduced its 1992 estimate for
the company from Dollars 2.05 a share to Dollars 2.25.
Among other stocks to post losses were IBM, down Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 90
1/2 , Walt Disney, Dollars  1/2 lower at Dollars 36 5/8 , Goodyear, down
Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 68 1/2 and Philip Morris, Dollars 2 weaker at
Dollars 74 1/8 .
Aetna Life bucked the trend, climbing Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 41 1/4 in
active trading after the company entered into a pact to sell its American Re
unit to a company formed by the reinsurance subsidiary's management and
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, the buy-out specialists.
Super Valu firmed Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 25 1/2 and Wetterau soared Dollars
6 3/8 to Dollars 30 3/8 on the news that the two companies, which are among
the biggest food distributors in the US, will merge in a deal said to be
worth Dollars 1.1bn.
Gencorp rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 14 1/8 after reporting second quarter
net income of 43 cents a share, up from 39 cents a share a year ago.
On the Nasdaq market, MCI Communications eased Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 32
3/4 as investors continued to digest the implications of the death of Mr
William McGowan, the longtime chairman of the telecoms group.
Canada
TORONTO prices closed lower in moderate activity which was boosted by three
large block trades.
Based on preliminary data, the TSE 300 index fell 8.39 points, or 0.25 per
cent, to 3,386.09. Declining issues led advances 321 to 256. Volume was
35.9m shares, up sharply from the previous 20.8m, and trading value was
CDollars 397.3m against CDollars 254.2m.
Tuesday's volume included three blocks - two in Mackenzie Financial
totalling about 7m shares, and one in Investors Group at 3.3m shares. Among
the sub-indices, ten of the 14 were lower. Financial services, mining,
energy and consumer products were all down somewhat and industrial products
group ended flat.
</TEXT>
