<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / International Company News: US wholesale food distributors
in Dollars 1.1bn merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO of the largest wholesale food distributors in the US - Super Valu and
Wetterau - yesterday announced plans to merge their operations, in a deal
said to be worth around Dollars 1.1bn.
Assuming the transaction goes ahead and does not fall foul of the
competition authorities, the combined company would outstrip Oklahoma-based
Fleming Companies as the nation's largest wholesale food distributor.
Under the outline merger agreement, Super Valu would make a cash offer of
Dollars 30.20 for each Wetterau share, valuing the common stock at Dollars
643.3m. It would also take on Dollars 440m of outstanding Wetterau debt,
creating the overall Dollars 1.1bn price tag.
Ahead of this transaction, Missouri-based Wetterau would also 'demerge' its
Shop 'n Save subsidiary, distributing 70 per cent of retailer's shares to
existing Wetterau shareholders and retaining the remaining 30 per cent.
Shop 'n Save currently comprises a chain of 28 'superwarehouse' food retail
outlets, based in eastern Missori and Illinois. Its annual sales are about
Dollars 500m and operating profits about Dollars 10m.
plies around 2,650 supermarkets and food retail outlets in 31 states, mostly
operated by independent retailers. It also has around 105 retail outlets of
its own. Total sales last year were Dollars 10.6bn.
Wetterau, meanwhile, distributes food and non-food products to about 2,850
retailers and over 1,200 institutional customers in 29 states.
Both companies said yesterday that the rationale behind the deal was
potential operating efficiencies and greater geographical reach.
However, Moody's, the Wall Street rating agency, said that it was placing
debt ratings of both companies on review for a possible downgrade. Moody's
acknowledged that there could be operating cost benefits from the merger,
but noted that the food distribution industry has been hit food price
deflation, weak consumer spending and increased competition.
Shares in Wetterau, quoted on the NASDAQ over-the-counter market and
currently ranking as the nation's third-largest grocery wholesaler, jumped
Dollars 6 3/8 to Dollars 30 3/8 yesterday, while Super Valu, the
second-largest food distributor, lost Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 25 1/4 .
</TEXT>
