FT  10 JUN 92 / Generators warned on long-term coal deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S privatised elec-tricity generating companies came under pressure
yesterday from Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, not to
drive too hard a bargain with British Coal in the current negotiations over
long-term coal supply.
The outcome of those negotiations will crucially affect both the value of
British Coal when it is privatised next summer and also the number of pits
that will remain viable.
Addressing the annual conference of the Union of Democratic Mineworkers
(UDM) in Weymouth, Mr Heseltine stressed repeatedly that it was not the job
of government to intervene directly in the negotiations.
But, in line with his interventionist instincts, he added: 'Remember when
you are negotiating these contracts that you are determining the future
availability of a national resource for which you will have longer-term
need.
'Remember also that you are talking about communities of men and women whose
lives will be affected by your decisions.'
His comments follow indications that the generators are ready to buy about
45m tonnes of coal a year, falling gradually to 30m. The current agreement,
which runs out next year, commits the generators to buy 65m tonnes.
Mr Heseltine guaranteed that British Coal employees would get a stake in its
future, whatever form of privatisation is chosen.
He said that no final decision had yet been taken on how to privatise
British Coal. He expressed sympathy, however, for the UDM-led consortium
which aims to take a 25 per cent stake in the corpor-ation.
Mr Roy Lynk, president of the UDM, said he would approach British Coal board
members to join the consortium as well as the main management unions. Mr
Lynk welcomed Mr Heseltine's speech, as a 'green light' for the UDM-led bid.
