<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Four convicted in biggest UK insider dealing prosecution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR former employees of finan-cial institutions, alleged to have been part
of the first insider dealing ring to be prosecuted, were convicted at the
Old Bailey yesterday.
At the end of the biggest UK insider dealing prosecution, which, with the
Department of Trade and Industry investigation which preceded it, is
understood to have cost about Pounds 350,000, Judge Laughland spoke of a
'web of illegality'.
He said tape recordings of telephone conversations between the four
displayed 'greedy cynicism' in 'brazen defiance' of the law passed to
inhibit insider dealing.
'You were part of a network of associates who thought it right quite openly
to defy the restrictions on the communication of inside information, for
your own financial benefit.
'The mischief of your offences is that they are, if uncontrolled,
destructive of the confidence which the international financial community
reposes in the City.'
Damage had been done not only to other investors or potential investors in
the City but to the whole financial community and to the public, the judge
said.
He said Mr David Gray, formerly a stockbroker with Morgan Grenfell
Securities, had been 'very much at the centre of this web of illegality'. Mr
Gray was given concurrent six-month prison sentences, suspended for two
years, and fined Pounds 5,000, on each of two convictions of dealing on the
basis of price sensitive information.
He was conditionally discharged for 12 months on each of five charges of
communicating information, to four of which he had pleaded guilty. He was
also ordered to pay Pounds 10,000 towards the prosecution costs.
Mr William Liggins, a former Lazards fund manager, was fined Pounds 5,000 on
a dealing charge, conditionally discharged for 12 months on a communicating
charge and ordered to pay Pounds 5,000 costs.
Miss Catherine Rowlands, formerly in Samuel Montagu's corporate finance
department, was given a 12-month conditional discharge for a communicating
offence. She must pay Pounds 2,000 costs.
Mr Mark Riding, former fund manager with the Co-operative Insurance Society
in Manchester, convicted on two dealing charges, was fined a total of Pounds
10,000, with Pounds 5,000 costs.
The offences related to two takeover bids in 1988. Hawthorn Leslie Group,
the USM-quoted cellular phone company, acquired ECT Cellular and London Car
Telephones, and Goodman Fielder Wattie, an Australian company, made a bid,
which lapsed, for Ranks Hovis McDougall, the UK foods group.
After the verdicts, Mr Peter Clarke, prosecuting for the DTI, said the case
stemmed from an investigation into dealings in shares of Pleasurama, the
leisure group, at the time of a bid by Mecca Leisure.
During the trial the judge directed the jury to acquit the four, and their
original co-defendant, Mr Keith Tondeur, former head of principal trading
and sales with Banque Paribas, on seven charges related to dealings in
Pleasurama shares.
</TEXT>
