FT  10 JUN 92 / Observer: Marshalls law
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
No doubt the great and the good attending today's CBI conference on
corporate governance will continue to huff and puff about the need for
non-executive directors. But are the institutions which put up the money
doing any more than pay lip service to the idea?
Take yesterday's Pounds 20m rights issue from Marshalls, the Halifax-based
building materials firm. After 22 years at the helm, David Marshall stepped
down as chairman last year handing over to brother Andrew. Although the
Marshall family does not have a huge stake in the company, six out of the
eight directors in its last annual report were called Marshall.
Like most firms in its industry, Marshalls is going through a bit of a rough
patch and it might have been thought that the City would insist on a few
non-executive directors to keep an eye on the shop in return for
underwriting the new capital. However, adviser Samuel Montagu insists that
'these guys are straightforward Yorkshire folk' and sees no need for them to
bow to the latest fashion.
