<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Clash over job opportunities for
minorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ATTEMPTS to compel companies to provide jobs for a specified proportion of
the ethnic minority communities in their area might 'backfire,' Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the home secretary, warned in the Commons last night.
Reaffirming the government's determination to combat racial discrimination,
he said, however, that subjecting employers to a legal requirement to
achieve target numbers would be a difficult and dangerous course to follow.
Mr Clarke emphasised that it would be damaging to race relations if white
members of the workforce believed that their black colleagues were there
only because the law required them to be admitted, regardless of their
suitability for the job.
He said the Commission on Racial Equality (CRE) would have to produce 'a
strong argument' if it wished to move the government in such a direction.
Mr Roy Hattersley, Labour's deputy leader, who opened a debate on the ethnic
minorities in British society, argued that a disproportionate number of
British black and Asian people were unemployed, and that they suffered from
a lack of equality in job opportunities.
He rejected the imposition of quotas or 'positive discrimination' but called
for the CRE to monitor the results of employers' efforts to ensure that
their workforce was 'fundamentally representative' of the local population.
Mr Hattersley urged that the monitoring process should be reinforced by the
government refusing to award contracts to companies that could not
demonstrate that they operated 'fair employment policies'.
The home secretary reaffirmed his commitment to monitoring as part of a
positive employment policy which good employers should follow.
But he insisted that the government could not accept the kind of compliance
which some Labour-controlled local authorities had sought to impose.
Mr Bernie Grant, the black Labour MP for Tottenham, gave a warning that high
unemployment and youth service cuts meant young people had nowhere to go and
were turning to drug trafficking.
He said: 'Youth workers tell me there is tension on the streets, that youths
are planning Los Angeles-style riots or disturbances in my area, and that
unless something is done, especially in the summer, we can expect trouble'.
A Labour motion calling on the government to introduce and implement
policies which would eventually eliminate the disadvantages suffered by
ethnic minorities was defeated by a majority of 47 (311-264).
</TEXT>
