<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Staff relocation pledge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE continuing depression in the housing market has contributed to a
Treasury decision enabling departments to make more generous arrangements
for civil servants forced to relocate and facing losses if they sell their
homes.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary, said yesterday that the
government is to make provision for staff who find that the sale of their
previous property is not enough to repay their mortgage.
Departments will be able to offer people in this category loans on
commercial terms and, in particularly difficult cases, offer advances of
salary to meet mortgage shortfalls.
The decision comes just a week after Mr Michael Howard, the environment
secretary, announced that 2,000 officials in his department were to move to
Docklands, but is primarily directed at the relocation of civil servants out
of the south-east.
When the Docklands plan was announced more than 1,000 DoE civil servants
held an angry meeting in protest. The meeting, which was organised by four
Civil Service unions, heard calls for industrial action to stop the move.
London and the south-east have been among the areas where property prices
have been particularly affected by the slump over the past two years or so.
About 3,000 staff from the Ministry of Defence are planned to move to
Bristol, more than 1,000 Inland Revenue staff are to go to Nottingham, while
part of the Home Office is moving to Derby and part of the Department of
Health is moving to Leeds.
The new arrangements will not necessarily mean more money is available, but
will give departments greater flexibility.
</TEXT>
