FT  10 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Warning on tram funding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOWNS and cities hoping to install modern tram systems similar to that
recently opened in Manchester have been told by the Transport Department
that their plans will have to wait.
They have been been given advance warning by Mr Roger Freeman, minister for
public transport, that the autumn public-spending round will contain no
money for any new schemes to go ahead in the next financial year.
The principal victim of the crack-down will be the West Midlands, which had
hoped to get the go-ahead for Line One of the Midland Metro from Birmingham
to Wolverhampton.
Midland Metro had already received Pounds 4.5m in government grants for
preparatory work on the line, and felt confident that the government would
give it the money to start construction next year.
Other towns and cities facing postponement of their projects are Nottingham
in the east Midlands, Leeds in West Yorkshire and Croydon, Surrey. The
planned Sheffield supertram system in South Yorkshire, however, will proceed
as planned because construction has already started.
Mr Freeman's announcement of the cash freeze on new tram projects is an
early indication of the pressure which spending ministers will face in this
year's spending round. There are fears in the public transport sector that
rail, bus, tram and underground projects will be squeezed to preserve the
Transport Department's Pounds 2bn-a-year roadbuilding programme.
</TEXT>
