damages of more than Pounds 1m for wrongful dismissal and breach of
contract.
Mr Hunt said in written evidence that Mr Botnar 'is personally involved in
all aspects of the business and he makes all important strategic decisions.
It is well accepted that the directors delegate their authority to Mr Botnar
to bind the company on their behalf.'
He said it was the 'personal control of Mr Botnar which distinguishes Nissan
(UK) from other companies in the motor industry. There is a lack of formal
structure and bureaucracy.'
In cross-examination, Mr Hunt said Mr Botnar was in Switzerland. A warrant
for the arrest of Mr Botnar has been issued by the Inland Revenue, and he
has submitted only written evidence.
Mr Botnar, in written evidence, said: 'Cholaj was responsible for the fleet
market as soon as he joined and he remained responsible for it throughout
his employment.'
He alleged that Mr Cholaj wanted 'to play up the secondary responsibilities'
given to him such as finance, advertising, or printing brochures, while
omitting to discuss his performance in fleet sales. He said Mr Cholaj's
allegations were 'frivolous, trivial, distorted, inaccurate'.
Commenting on one of Mr Cholaj's allegations, Mr Botnar said: 'If I asked
Cholaj to curtail a meeting, it would have been because I do not consider
lengthy and fruitless palaver of any variety to be useful for the company.'
The hearing continues today.
