FT  10 JUN 92 / Collector to chase penalised businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES that incur penalties for failing to file their accounts on time
with Companies House will be rapidly referred to a private debt collection
agency if they do not pay, it emerged yesterday.
From July 1 companies will be fined up to Pounds 5,000 if they do not file
accounts within the statutory period - seven months after the financial year
end for public companies and 10 months for private ones.
The Lewis Group beat Dun &amp; Bradstreet and Trade Indemnity for the contract
as collection agency to Companies House, an executive agency of the
Department of Trade and Industry. The contract comes as part of a clampdown
on late-filing companies.
Companies House has set a target of increasing the proportion of companies
that file on time from 80 per cent now to 91 per cent by 1995.
It will invoice late-filing companies for the penalties and forward
outstanding bills to Lewis after 30 days.
