FT  10 JUN 92 / DTI held up probe to let SFO act
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE appointment of Depart-ment of Trade and Industry inspectors to
investigate the Maxwell companies was delayed until the Serious Fraud Office
told officials of the direction its inquiry was taking into the affair, it
emerged yesterday.
It was not until two weeks ago - more than a year after the flotation of
Mirror Group Newspapers and seven months after Robert Maxwell died - that Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, decided the time was right.
Gathered with Mr Heseltine in his office were Mr Vivian Brown, head of the
DTI's investigations division, and Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs
minister. In front of them was a proposal for action.
The SFO inquiries would not encompass the extent to which company law may
have been breached during the MGN flotation in May last year, the report
said. That justified appointing DTI inspectors. The two ministers and Mr
Brown agreed.
An announcement was delayed to coincide with the Department of Social
Security announcement on Monday of an independent review of pension law.
Part of the value of launching an investigation, particularly when political
pressure is growing at Westminster, is the impression given of a government
acting on as many fronts as possible.
The DTI had been anxious to build its case carefully. Officials were
concerned about the cost - appointing inspectors can involve millions of
pounds - and the consequences of a wrong decision, both for the company and
for the DTI's reputation.
The official argument until this week - including under the tenure of Mr
Peter Lilley, former trade and industry secretary - was that there was no
point in the DTI's organising an investigation that might clash with that of
the SFO.
DTI officials meet the SFO formally four times a year, but are in closer
contact informally.
The timing of the appointment of DTI inspectors into the Maxwell affair was
 -according to insiders - therefore not a question of Mr Heseltine shaking
the department into action.
The argument being spread around Whitehall yesterday was that it was simply
propitious.
</TEXT>
