<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Maxwell pensioners criticise City firms: Lilley defends
Pounds 2.5m emergency aid limit - Campaigners confident on return of assets
/ Delay in appointing inspectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO PROMINENT city firms should have suspected in the year before Robert
Maxwell's death that they were aiding in the disappearance of securities
under their control, according to a High Court writ.
By late 1990, the writ alleges, the two firms knew or ought to have known
that transactions involving the securities had put the interests of
pensioners at risk. In spite of that, the writ alleges, the firms failed to
inform either pension fund trustees or regulators about those matters. In
the interim the securities were used as collateral for loans to Maxwell's
private interests.
The writ, filed last week, seeks Pounds 88m from the fund managers as well
as from Lehman Brothers and Credit Suisse, two investment banks that
received the securities allegedly stolen from the MGN pension scheme.
The writ, from the present trustees of the Mirror Group Newspapers pension
scheme, alleges that Invesco MIM and Capel-Cure Myers (CCM) failed to alert
either pension fund trustees or regulators. Instead, they sought assurances
from the people who gave the instructions that their activities were proper,
the writ says.
The two fund managers were allegedly told to hand over the pension scheme's
shares portfolios to two other Maxwell-owned fund managers to be used for
what was described as stock lending. The writs allege that the fund managers
acted on instructions from people who had no authority to order stock
lending and that all signs pointed to stock lending of a highly irregular
nature.
The document for the first time spells out in explicit detail just how the
theft of assets from the pension funds was allegedly effected.
It claims that, as early as October 18 1990, MIM must have had suspicions
about the stock lending it was being asked to undertake because it wrote to
London and Bishopsgate International Investment Management (LBI) asking to
be released from all responsibility for the securities while they were in
LBI's care.
The writ says that on October 26 MIM's suspicions should have been further
aroused because it learned that loaned securities, originally made out in
favour of Bishopsgate Investment Management (another Maxwell fund manager),
had been returned without being made out in the name of the borrower, as is
the usual practice.
The writ says: 'The plaintiff will contend that MIM knew at all material
times after October 26 1990 that legitimate stock lending was not being
undertaken by BIM or LBI and that therefore the delivered MIM portfolio was
at risk.'
Then, the writ says, at a meeting with several MGN pension trustees on
December 3 1990, MIM was told stock lending would end and securities would
be returned. But on December 18, in a letter from Mr Kevin Maxwell and Mr
Trevor Cook, secretary to the scheme, MIM was allegedly told lending would
be extended to the end of January.
Each month thereafter, MIM allegedly received a letter saying lending would
be extended for yet one more month, that trustees were very happy with the
stock lending programme and that hefty fees were being earned. The writ says
that the fees were never passed on to MIM and were far larger than could
have been earned through conventional stock lending activities.
By April last year, it is alleged, MIM was so worried about stock lending
that its compliance officer sought an outside legal opinion on the matter.
An internal meeting was held that month, the writ claims, at which MIM
officials recorded concerns that stocks were not being loaned through a
conventional money broker. By August 15 1991, MIM allegedly knew that the
assets it had passed to LBI for stock lending had been used as collateral -
knowledge which the writ says should have tipped it off to the fact that its
securities had been pledged as security for loans to a third party.
The allegations against CCM follow a similar pattern. On October 8 1990, CCM
was allegedly instructed by BIM and LBI to deliver a portfolio of stocks
directly to Lehman Brothers. The writ says that because conventional stock
lending must be conducted through recognised money brokers, CCM should have
been suspicious. It says: 'CCM was aware that the delivery of the delivered
CCM portfolio to Lehmans was to be used as 'loan collateral', which was
plainly an improper purpose . . .'
Indeed, the writ alleges, by December 12 1990, CCM's own file notes refer to
the fact that it knew securities were being used as loan collateral.
Lehman Brothers said it accepted the securities in good faith and intends to
contest the writ. Invesco MIM said it believed at all times that it was
following instructions of all the MGN pension-scheme trustees. The other two
firms declined to comment.
</TEXT>
