<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Receivers blame move by Libya for failure of AWD
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN UNDISCLOSED deal to supply 2,000 trucks to Libya, which the country
failed to complete, was primarily responsible for AWD, the former Bedford
trucks business, going into receivership last week.
When Libya did not sign a Pounds 117m letter of credit, it was 'the straw
which broke the camel's back', joint receivers Mr Tony Thompson and Mr Roger
Oldfield, of accountants KPMG Peat Marwick, acknowledged yesterday.
Intermediaries between Libya and the company say they believe the reasons
for the Libyans' failure to complete the deal are political. But they have
not been able to establish whether it represents retaliation by the
country's ruler, Col Muammer Gadaffi, against United Nations sanctions.
These were imposed in April because of Libya's refusal to hand over for
trial two men suspected of involvement in the Lockerbie bombing.
Under the agreement, Libya was to have taken delivery of the 2,000 trucks
within a 12-month period starting this year. It would have thrown a lifeline
to AWD, most of whose workforce had been idle since January as a result of
the recession in the UK truck market and the failure to complete another
large foreign supply agreement - 2,000 trucks for Iran.
AWD's management called in the receivers last week. The company, based in
Dunstable, Bedfordshire, and controlled by Mr David JB Brown, the
entrepreneur, and his family, is understood to owe its bank and other
creditors about Pounds 50m.
Truck production is being resumed at the plant today, but at a much reduced
level and with only 150 employees. The other 502 were made redundant on
Monday.
The Iranian deal, first announced last November, was said to be worth Pounds
70m to AWD. It is now known that AWD's directors were hoping that deal would
maintain the company's viability until the Libyan contract came on stream.
All the trucks would have been built at Dunstable, with the Iranian project
involving neither local assembly nor AWD taking an equity stake in an
assembly joint venture.
The receivers say several 'substantial' companies are interested in buying
AWD as a going concern.
Mr Thompson said that the Iranian deal was 'still close to completion' and
that the Libyans 'still apparently want to do a deal'.
</TEXT>
