<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Investment regulation criticised: Reports from OFT say
commissions paid to sales agents could distort advice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO INDEPENDENT reports published yesterday by the Office of Fair Trading
contain the disquieting conclusions that investors know too little about the
financial products they buy to make a sensible choice and that commissions
paid to sales agents could distort investment advice.
The reports' broader finding is that competition in the marketplace for
financial services is not working in the interest of the consumer.
The reports are fiercely critical of the regulation of retail investments.
The OFT asked two consumer affairs consultants, Mr Jeremy Mitchell and Ms
Helena Wiesner, for separate reports. Both found there were 'market
failures' in financial services, resulting from public ignorance and the
commissions paid to intermediaries.
One report said: 'A commission-based remuneration system poses substantial
conflicts of interest for intermediaries and can have a deleterious effect
on the type of product a consumer is advised to buy, and for independent
financial advisers, also on the company from which that product is bought.'
It also criticised the scope of retail regulation, and the fact that
building societies are not regulated under the Financial Services Act.
If the OFT accepted the reports' conclusions Sir Gordon Borrie, the
director-general of fair trading, would be brought into conflict with the
Securities and Investments Board, which regulates most of the financial
services industry.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, would then be called on to make a final
decision. The OFT stressed, however, that the reports were aimed at
'stimulating discussion'. The reports had revealed much useful information.
SIB announced last month it would not force independent financial advisers
to reveal the commissions they received from investment companies in cash
terms at point of sale.
It also allowed life companies to quote illustrations for potential buyers
on the assumption that their costs were in line with the industry average -
even if their expenses were much higher.
Both decisions are attacked in the OFT's reports, which said: 'Clear
information about costs and other features of the product or service are
essential. This is patently not the case as far as the provision of
independent advice is concerned.'
When Sir David Walker, out-going chairman of SIB, announced the results of
his review, he admitted he disagreed with Sir Gordon on commission
disclosure. He added: 'Ultimately, if he persists in his view, and I persist
in mine, then we will have to leave ministers to decide.'
The OFT will be unable to act until SIB's proposed rules have been fully
drafted, which will probably not be until the end of next month.
Mr Mitchell, a former director of the National Consumer Council and director
of consumer affairs at the OFT, and Ms Wiesner, a director of the Life
Assurance and Unit Trust Regulatory Office (Lautro), agree on several
points:
Levels of commission may influence the advice of salesmen. That is
illustrated by growth in the sale of endowment mortgages, which pay a
commission not available for standard repayment mortgages. In 1970,
endowments accounted for 6.7 per cent of mortgages and repayments for 88 per
cent. In 1990, endowments took 75 per cent of mortgages and repayments only
20 per cent.
The drive by life companies to secure sales outlets, particularly with
building societies, has pushed up commission levels. 'Tied agency' deals, in
which a building society sells only the products of one life office, have
proved very popular. Only two large building societies, Bradford &amp; Bingley
and Yorkshire, remain independent in that respect.
According to Ms Wiesner's report, Halifax Building Society, which is tied to
Standard Life, the UK's largest mutual life insurer, received Pounds 162m in
commission in 1990 - 16 per cent of income and 27 per cent of profits.
Since 1989, the share taken by commission from a 10-year endowment policy
has risen by 27 per cent for independents and 47 per cent for tied agents.
According to Lautro's last commission survey, the highest commission paid on
a Pounds 50-a-month, 25-year endowment policy with a tied agent was Pounds
642. High turnover of sales staff may have implications for their training
and competence. On average, 38 per cent of new sales recruits to life
insurance companies leave within a year and 54 per cent leave within two.
One office, Provident Mutual, loses 90 per cent of recruits in two years.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
