<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / World Trade News: US targets EC products for retaliation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MRS CARLA HILLS, the US trade representative, yesterday released a list of
Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.08bn) worth of EC products potentially targeted for
high import tariffs in retaliation for the loss of European market share by
US soyabean producers.
'We have gone the extra mile, patiently pursuing this issue through the
General Agreement for Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) for five years,' she said in
an accompanying statement.
'However, in light of the magnitude of trade harm the US is suffering, I
have no choice but to prepare a commensurate trade action.'
The list - probably the largest ever compiled for a trade action - included:
EC wines, cheeses, beers, meat products, seafood, breads, vegetables, gin,
vermouth, brandy, whiskey, unmanufactured tobacco, animal feed, cut flowers,
vegetables and cooking oils.
The US trade representative will now hear public comment for at least 30
days before paring the list of targets from Dollars 2bn to Dollars 1bn and
putting the sanctions in effect.
Two dispute settlement panels in the Gatt have found the EC at fault for
subsidies of its oilseeds sector. EC subsidy schemes have boosted domestic
output of oilseeds by more than 10m tonnes since the early 1980s.
The EC has said it plans to offer compensation to the US, as well as
Argentina and Brazil, but the Bush administration is being urged by the farm
lobby to accept no settlement that does not benefit the soyabean producers.
</TEXT>
