<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / EC accord lays base for single securities market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FOUNDATIONS of a single European market in securities trading were laid
early this morning in Luxembourg by European Community finance ministers.
They reached preliminary agreement on rules to harmonise capital
requirements for European banks and securities firms.
The ministers and European Commission officials finally agreed the key
points of the draft capital adequacy directive shortly after midnight
following more than nine hours of talks.
The directive will lay out the regulatory framework for the single market,
putting securities firms and banks' trading operations on the same footing.
The agreement is likely to give fresh impetus to the investment services
directive. This second measure, which would build on the capital adequacy
directive, would give securities firms a passport to operate throughout the
EC. However, it has been held up by disputes between groups of member states
led by France and Britain.
Britain, which takes over the EC presidency next month, has always said it
favours an investment services directive, but only on terms which do not
damage City firms.
Until the final hour of talks it looked as though an accord would again be
held up as Britain, Germany and France tried to defend their interests.
Officials were cautious about proclaiming a breakthrough, pointing out that
a number of technical issues needed to be resolved before formal agreement
could be reached. The whole measure will return to the finance ministers'
agenda on June 29 for political approval.
Sir Leon Brittan, the EC commissioner for financial services, welcomed the
deal and said afterwards: 'I have throughout made it clear that the purpose
of the directive is to lead to the opening of the European securities
market. This is now being done in a fair way which is guaranteed not to
damage the legitimate interests of any existing market.'
The agreement will apply to securities firms and to the part of banks'
balance sheets on which investment business is conducted - the so-called
'trading book'. If formally approved, the directive would theoretically take
effect from the beginning of next year, although implementation is likely to
take much longer. The main points of the deal include:
A flexible limit on the amount of capital which firms must have to back
single investments or 'large exposures'. Firms will be allowed a window of
10 days in which to breach existing limits restricting such investments to
25 per ent of their capital base. This should help preserve the
manoeuvrability of Britain's small merchant banks.
A choice of the limit on the amount of subordinated short-term debt firms
can count as capital for regulatory purposes. An agreement that will allow
corporate treasurers and pension funds, as well as banks and investment
firms, to carry out so-called repurchase agreements under the looser rules
of the capital adequacy directive.
A three-year review period to ensure that the directive continues to fit in
with international accords on capital adequacy, such as that proposed
between securities and banking regulators earlier this year.
Commission officials described the deal as 'a fairly uncomfortable
compromise' for everyone.
Tory split exploited Page 14
Germans likely to back UK on Brussels powers Page 2
