<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Majority of EC ministers oppose budget increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MAJORITY of European Community finance ministers yesterday came out
against an increase in the EC budget, widening the rift between rich and
poor member states.
Differences over the budget could dominate the Lisbon summit at the end of
this month, increasing the pressure on the Community following last week's
rejection of the Maastricht treaty by the Danish people.
Seven countries, led by the UK and Germany, said yesterday they wanted to
limit their budget contributions.
Only Spain, Portugal, Greece and Ireland - which stand to benefit the most
from an enlarged budget - backed the so-called Delors II package. Denmark
did not take part in the discussion. Mr Jacques Delors, Commission
president, and his fellow commissioners are calling for an increase in the
EC budget from Ecu66.6bn (Pounds 46.7bn) this year to Ecu87.5bn in 1997, at
current prices.
The budget row could have damaging effects in Ireland, which holds its
referendum on Maastricht next week. Pro-Maastricht campaigners in the
republic have made much of the financial benefits of closer union.
Ministers yesterday reaffirmed their commitment to continued economic
integration despite last week's Danish vote. But member states vary widely
in their enthusiasm for the budget proposals.
Richer member states want to limit their EC budget contribution to 1.2 per
cent of gross national product while they strain to meet criteria for
economic convergence imposed by the Maastricht treaty. They point out that
EC spending does not match contributions even at current levels, but the
Delors package proposes a gradual increase to 1.37 per cent of GNP by 1997.
Mr Horst Kohler, Germany's deputy finance minister, said yesterday such an
increase was unacceptable. Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor of the
exchequer, said the Delors proposals were not dead, but that there had been
some very blunt talking.
The finance ministers' conclusions will be submitted to foreign ministers
for their meeting, also in Luxembourg, on Monday. Mr Kohler said before the
debate that the budget should not be merely a list of the Commission's
wishes for which cash had to be found.
He said a failure to explain EC policymaking to the public might have been
one reason for last week's Danish vote.
Ministers also heard the tough judgments by the monetary committee of EC
national treasury officials and the EC financial watchdog, the Court of
Auditors.
Mr Cees Maas, who heads the committee, told ministers 'cohesion' funds for
poorer EC members should not be released until those nations had achieved
strict economic convergence targets.
EC finance ministers last night added harmonisation of indirect taxes to the
list of topics that EC leaders will be asked to discuss during the Lisbon
summit.
They will come back to the measures at a special extra council of ministers
on June 29, after EC leaders have glanced at them during the summit on June
26 and June 27.
Germans lay blame, Page 2
Labour exploits Tory split, Page 14
