<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / International Company News: Pechiney agrees to sale of
nuclear-related businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FRENCH government has asked Pechiney, the state-controlled aluminium
group, to sell for FFr2.2bn (Dollars 411m) its nuclear-related businesses,
in a reorganisation of one of the world's leading nuclear industries.
Pechiney has agreed to sell nearly all its nuclear businesses by the end of
the month to Framatome, France's monopoly builder of nuclear reactors, and
Cogema, the nuclear fuel retreatment group.
The companies for sale are Comurhex, a fuel refining group; FBFC, a fuel
producer; and Zircotube, a maker of zirconium tubes used in corrosion
resistant fuel claddings. In addition, Pechiney is selling a 50 per cent
stake in Cezus, the world's largest zirconium producer, to Framatome and
Cogema jointly, with an undertaking to sell them the rest at the end of
1994.
Pechiney's withdrawal from the nuclear industry, which accounted for 3 per
cent of its sales last year, leaves France with two nuclear industrial
groups: Cogema, which specialises in the fuel cycle from mining to
enrichment transport and waste storage; and Framatome, which makes reactors,
fuel and related products.
Mr Dominique Strauss-Kahn, industry minister, said the idea was to simplify
the industry's organisation to help it form international alliances.
Pechiney agreed to the nuclear disposals because it accepted it 'did not
have the right cards in its hand to follow its strategy in the long term' in
that sector, said Mr Jean Gandois, chairman. The French nuclear industry
needed 'fewer players, each with better defined powers'.
The businesses involved contributed between FFr130m and FFr140m to
Pechiney's FFr820m profits, and FFr2.2bn to its FFr74.4bn turnover last
year. This did not include Cezus, which remains a Pechniney subsidiary, with
Pechiney controlling of its titanium unit until its disposal is complete in
two years.
Cogema's sales, FFr21.7bn last year, will rise by between 6 and 7 per cent
thanks to the deal, while Framatome's nuclear-related turnover, FFr8.5bn in
1990, will grow by between 10 and 15 per cent.
Pechiney has been involved in the nuclear industry since the end of the
Second World War, when it was asked by the atomic energy commission to make
graphite for early experimental reactors. However, this has always been a
small part of its business. Mr Gandois said the cash would be used to reduce
Pechiney's borrowings of more than FFr20bn.
</TEXT>
