<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / International Company News: Aetna to sell reinsurance
offshoot in Dollars 1.4bn LBO
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AETNA Life &amp; Casualty, one of the largest US composite insurance companies,
is selling its reinsurance subsidiary to a buy-out vehicle for about Dollars
1.4bn.
The deal still requires regulatory approvals. If these are forthcoming, the
sale will represent a rare leveraged transaction in the US insurance
industry. It would also be one of the largest deals for months in the
dormant leveraged buy-out (LBO) market.
The buy-out company, called American Re-Insurance, has been formed by
Kohlberg, Kravis Roberts, the buy-out specialists, and the reinsurance
subsidiary's management. Aetna first disclosed that it was talking to KKR
about a buy-out in mid-April. Speculation on the price-tag had centred
around Dollars 1.4bn.
Aetna will get Dollars 1.21bn in cash at the closing date and up to Dollars
20m more in December. Aetna also receives Dollars 100m principal in
subordinated notes issued by American Re-Insurance, and Dollars 70m in 14
per cent pay-in-kind preferred stock. Aetna will keep most of American
Re-Insurance's UK-based operations, with a book value of Dollars 30m, and
take about Dollars 30m of ordinary shares in the buy-out company.
The deal will be financed by a mixture of equity, bank facilities and
publicly-traded debt securities. KKR said commitment letters had been
received from Chase Manhattan, Continental Bank and Westpac for senior bank
borrowings of Dollars 650m, and that Dollars 350m of debt securities would
be sold by Merrill Lynch.
Aetna bought the reinsurance company for Dollars 389m in 1979 and carries it
on its books at Dollars 740m. Assets of American Re-Insurance at
end-December were Dollars 3.8bn, and 1991 profits totalled Dollars 133m.
The sale follows a string of restructurings and asset sales by large US
insurers, attempting to bolster reserves and improve profits.
</TEXT>
