<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Sins of commission exact a price: A long dispute over
payments to intermediaries in the financial services industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'sins of commission' came back to haunt the UK's financial services
industry yesterday.
Two reports issued yesterday by the Office of Fair Trading conclude that
consumers know too little about the financial products they buy to choose
them wisely and that commissions paid to sales agents distort those choices.
Most financial intermediaries are paid by commission for each sale they
make. The level of commission varies substantially between products and
between companies.
This report revives a long-running dispute within the industry and raises
the question of whether self-regulation is workable for the industry.
Regulation has been controversial ever since the Financial Services Act
(FSA) became law in 1988, but the publication at the end of last month of
the conclusions of the Securities and Investments Board's 13-month retail
investment review was supposed to put the issue to rest.
The OFT's reports attack SIB's conclusions on commission disclosure -
forcing intermediaries to disclose what they have been paid by product
providers - but they also throw into question the scope of the entire
regulatory regime.
Mr Jeremy Mitchell, a former director of the National Consumer Council and
director of consumer affairs at the OFT, and Ms Helena Wiesner, a director
of Lautro, the Life Assurance and Unit Trust Regulatory Office, produced
independent reports.
They agreed on several points.
Levels of commission may influence the advice of salesmen. That is
illustrated by growth in the sale of endowment mortgages, which pay a
commission not available for standard repayment mortgages. In 1970,
endowments accounted for 6.7 per cent of mortgages and repayments for 88 per
cent. In 1990, endowments took 75 per cent of mortgages and repayments only
20 per cent.
Endowments are less flexible and often more expensive than their repayment
counterparts, according to Ms Wiener, who believes the high rate of
surrender of such policies gives 'considerable grounds for concern'.
The drive by life companies to secure sales outlets, particularly with
building societies, has pushed up commission levels. 'Tied agency' deals, in
which a building society sells only the products of one life office, have
proved very popular, and only two large building societies, Bradford &amp;
Bingley and Yorkshire, remain independent.
According to Ms Wiesner's report, Halifax building society, which is tied to
Standard Life, the UK's largest mutual life insurer, received Pounds 162m in
commission during 1990 - 16 per cent of income and 27 per cent of profits.
Since 1989, the share taken by commission from a 10-year endowment policy
has risen by 27 per cent for independents and 47 per cent for tied agents.
According to Lautro's last commission survey, the highest commission paid on
a Pounds 50-a-month, 25-year endowment policy at a tied agent was Pounds 642
 -more than the whole first year's premiums.
High turnover of sales staff may have implications for their training and
competence. On average, 38 per cent of new sales recruits to life insurance
companies leave within a year and 54 per cent leave within two. One office,
Provident Mutual, loses 90 per cent of recruits within two years.
Ms Wiesner says a company representative leaving a company may encourage
people he or she has advised to surrender their policies and invest with a
new company.
SIB decided not to force intermediaries to disclose their commissions
because direct sales forces and tied agents could not be made to do the
same.
That would put independents at a disadvantage as SIB forces independents to
disclose their commissions, if asked, once a sale has been completed.
Ms Wiesner rejects that argument, saying independent advice is worth paying
for, and that consumers should know the true price.
The OFT reports agree with SIB in one area. Sir David Walker, outgoing
chairman of SIB, called the scope of regulation under the FSA into question.
He pointed out that insurance products come under one regime, but building
society accounts, which most consumers regard as closely comparable, are
regulated by another - the Building Societies Commission.
Mr Mitchell pointed to the levels of compensation a consumer could expect
for different investments.
An investor claiming compensation on an investment of Pounds 60,000 could
expect a maximum of Pounds 60,000 if the investment were covered by the Law
Society or the Policyholders' Protection Act, but only Pounds 18,000 for a
building society deposit, and Pounds 15,000 for a bank deposit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-3731</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFJA2AA2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Future looks up for Scots engineers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGINEERING companies in Scotland reported a modest rise in optimism
yesterday. Intake of orders and capital investment had increased, with the
electronics industry and medium-sized engineering companies reporting growth
while heavy engineering had a drop in orders.
Scottish Engineering, which published its quarterly survey for the three
months to June of its 300 members as well as some electronics companies that
are not members, said the survey showed a 'positive move out of the depths
of recession across the industry'.
The level of job losses was slowing down, the survey said.
The proportion of companies reporting increased optimism about their
prospects was 41 per cent, compared with 32 per cent in the previous survey,
which covered the period to the end of February.
The proportion saying their optimism was unchanged was static at 44 per
cent.
In the electronics sector, some 42 per cent of companies said their orders
had increased, while 28 per cent said they had declined.
In heavy engineering, though, more companies reported a fall in orders than
reported an increase.
The foundry sector appeared to have arrested its orders decline, but
improvement was patchy.
Only light engineering companies said they had increased their staffing
level, while other parts of the industry were still shedding labour.
Overtime worked was falling, with the heavy engineering sector showing the
sharpest fall.
On capital investment, 18 per cent of companies said they were increasing
their spending while 19 per cent said they were reducing it. The rest
reported no change. The electronics sector reported the biggest increase in
investment in training.
</TEXT>
