<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Battle for Sarajevo continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERB forces resumed their bombardment of Sarajevo yesterday and street
battles flared again in the Bosnian capital where many of the 300,000
encircled residents, including Serbs, face starvation, Reuter reports from
Belgrade.
Fighting broke out towards midday after Serb forces held their fire during
the night, regrouping after suffering their first setback in a two-month
siege.
Residents described the renewed fighting as intermittent shelling, less
intense than on Monday when Sarajevo's Moslem and Croat defenders, defying a
two-month siege by Serb irregulars, staged their first counter-offensive
after three days of blistering Serb bombardments. The fighting left streets
littered with bodies and rubble and handed the Serb irregulars ringing
Sarajevo their first setback. Unofficial estimates said dozens of people
were killed and more than 350 wounded.
Moslem and Croat forces yesterday fought to hold positions seized from Serb
irregulars in Vraca, Vidikovac and Zuc, one of the main positions for firing
artillery, rockets and mortars at Sarajevo.
Local journalists said there was fighting around Nedjarici, with the Moslem
and Croat defence forces trying to push towards the Serb-held airport.
Military observers and diplomats said it was not possible to tell how many
fighters were in the hills or in the city. They said there were certainly
more than 20,000 on each side waging what appears to be the key battle of
the Bosnian conflict.
</TEXT>
