FT  10 JUN 92 / Irish parties urge 'Yes' vote on Maastricht Treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADERS of Ireland's four main political parties made a joint call
yesterday for a 'yes' vote in the referendum on the Maastricht Treaty which
is to be held on June 18.
In a rare display of cross-party unity, the leaders of Fianna Fail, Fine
Gael, Labour and the Progressive Democrats, which between them represent 153
of the 166 seats in the Irish parliament (Dail), said that following
Denmark's rejection of the Treaty, 'it is, more than ever, vitally important
for Ireland, and for Europe, that the people of Ireland vote 'Yes' . . . a
'No' vote would be clearly against our national interest'.
Of particular importance for Ireland is the proposed doubling of EC
structural and cohesion funds for the four 'Objective 1' countries, made
under the Delors II proposals, and under which Ireland would hope to obtain
IPounds 6bn (Pounds 5.5bn) for the 1994-98 period, as opposed to IPounds 3bn
for 1989-93. Both the UK and Germany have expressed strong reservations over
the Delors II package, as they would be the main contributors.
Mr Bertie Ahern, the finance minister, was yesterday expected to emphasise
to his fellow-EC finance ministers the importance of the funds for Ireland
and for Irish voters' perceptions of the Maastricht Treaty. He is hoping to
be able to bring back to Dublin some reassurances that the money will indeed
be available.
Mr Albert Reynolds, the prime minister, warned yesterday, however, that
Ireland 'would not even have a place at the negotiating table' to argue for
its share of the structural funds if the country votes 'No'.
