<PROFILE>_AN-CFJA2AACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920610
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 92 / Regulators disagree on state of financial services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY may be called on to settle a dispute between regulators
following the publication yesterday by the Office of Fair Trading of two
reports which fiercely criticise the regulation of retail investments.
The OFT asked two consumer affairs consultants, Jeremy Mitchell and Helena
Wiesner, to prerpare separate reports. Both found that there were 'market
failures' in financial services, resulting from public ignorance and the
commissions paid to intermediaries.
One report said: 'A commission-based remuneration system poses substantial
conflicts of interest for intermediaries and can have a deleterious effect
on the type of product a consumer is advised to buy, and for independent
financial advisers, also on the company from which that product is bought.'
It also criticised the scope of retail regulation, and the fact that
building societies, unlike insurance and other investment products, are not
regulated under the Financial Services Act.
If the OFT accepts the reports' conclusions, Sir Gordon Borrie, the
director-general of fair trading, would be brought into direct conflict with
the Securities and Investments Board, which regulates most of the financial
services industry.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, would then be called on to make a final
decision. However, the OFT stressed the reports were aimed at 'stimulating
discussion' and did not commit the office to the recommendations. It said
the reports had revealed much useful information.
The SIB announced last month it would not force independent financial
advisers to reveal the commissions they received from investment companies
in cash terms at point of sale.
It also allowed life companies to quote illustrations for potential buyers
on the assumption that their costs were in line with the industry average -
even if their expenses were much higher.
Both decisions are attacked in the OFT's reports, which said: 'Clear
information about costs and other features of the product or service are
essential. This is patently not the case as far as the provision of
independent advice is concerned.'
When Sir David Walker, out-going chairman of the SIB, announced the results
of his review, he admitted he disagreed with Sir Gordon on commission
disclosure. He added: 'Ultimately, if he persists in his view, and I persist
in mine, then we will have to leave ministers to decide.'
The OFT will be unable to act until the SIB's proposed rules have been fully
drafted, which will probably not be until the end of next month. At that
point, the director-general could advise Mr Lamont to change the proposals.
Sins of commission, Page 7
</TEXT>
