<DATE>920609
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / International Company News: McGowan, MCI chairman and
telecom visionary, dies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR WILLIAM McGowan, chairman of MCI Communications and one of the most
important figures behind the revolutionary changes in the structure of the
US telecommunications industry over the past two decades, died yesterday in
Washington of a heart attack. He was 64.
Mr McGowan, a restless challenger of convention, came to the rescue of a
tiny, financially-ailing start-up company - then known as Microwave
Communications Incorporated - in 1968 and turned it into the second-largest
long-distance telephone company in the US.
Central to his success was the legal challenge he mounted to mighty American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, which led in 1978 to a landmark court ruling breaking
AT&amp;T's monopoly of the long-distance telephone market.
Mr McGowan, who for most of his career was a chain-smoking workaholic,
suffered a serious heart attack in 1986. He underwent heart transplant
surgery the next year but returned to his desk after only a few months,
declaring 'it would be punishment not to work'.
However, in recent years he had steadily withdrawn from day-to-day
responsibilities at MCI and late last year he ceded his role as chief
executive to Mr Bert Roberts, MCI's president and his long-time heir
apparent. Mr Roberts is expected to be named chairman.
Wall Street analysts said Mr McGowan's death was likely to have little
impact on MCI's operations, in view of the careful devolution of power to Mr
Roberts.
However, they said the US telecommunications industry as a whole would
suffer from the loss of one of its most articulate and visionary spokesmen.
MCI's shares closed at Dollars 32 7/8 , up Dollars  5/8 on the Nasdaq
over-the-counter market.
Mr McGowan, a florid-faced man with a broad grin, was born into an Irish
immigrant family in Pennsylvania. His father was a railroad engineer and his
mother a teacher. After attending the Harvard Business School, he set up in
New York as a consultant rescuing troubled companies.
In 1968 he was invited to help rescue MCI, then based in Chicago, which
wanted to offer a radio telephone services to trucks travelling between that
city and St Louis.
The company needed approval for this service from the Federal Communications
Commission, which oversees the US telecommunications industry, but its
application was opposed by AT&amp;T, which had a virtual monopoly in the
long-distance market.
MCI eventually won FCC approval and Mr McGowan, having taken control of the
company after paying off its debts, got a taste for challenging AT&amp;T. It was
his particular genius to realise that a tightly run rival could undercut the
giant's prices and that AT&amp;T's heavy-handed approach to potential
competition made it vulnerable on anti-trust grounds.
Over the subsequent decade and a half, MCI constantly harried AT&amp;T before
regulatory agencies and in the courts, to the extent that the company
jokingly became known as ' a law firm with an antenna on the roof'.
Mr McGowan, aware that good relations with the FCC would be vital to his
crusade, quickly moved the company's headquarters to Washington, just around
the corner from the commission's offices.
Parallel with MCI's attacks on AT&amp;T, the Justice Department pursued the
giant on anti-trust grounds, and Mr McGowan's ultimate vindication came in
1984 when this suit led to the break-up of AT&amp;T and the spinning-off of its
local telephone services into seven separate 'Baby Bell' regional companies.
This created a much more level playing field for MCI and other independents,
such as Sprint, to compete against AT&amp;T in the long-distance market. A
bitter price war ensued, which helped the US consumer but in 1986
contributed to huge losses at MCI and heavy staff cuts.
MCI recovered, helped by innovative product introductions, and it is now
estimated to hold some 17 per cent of the long-distance market - although an
aggressive AT&amp;T has made it much harder for MCI to win further domestic
market share.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-3784</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFIBTAFUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920609
