<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / US utilities to merge in Dollars 2.3bn deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ENTERGY Corporation, a large Louisiana-based electric utility, is making a
Dollars 2.3bn (Pounds 1.3bn) cash-and-stock offer to acquire Gulf States
Utilities (GSU), a Texas-based utility, in an agreed takeover that could
help rationalise the electricity market in the region.
The terms of the deal - which would make the combined group one of the top
five utilities in the US - call for Entergy to offer up to Dollars 250m in
cash and the remaining Dollars 2.05bn in stock.
The takeover values GSU at Dollars 20 per share, representing a 38 per cent
premium over its closing price last Friday.
Yesterday the GSU share price rose by Dollars 1 1/4 , or 8.6 per cent, to
close at Dollars 15 3/4 . Entergy's share price declined by Dollars 1/8 to
Dollars 27.
Entergy is a large New Orleans-based utility serving more than 1.7m
customers in Arkansas, Louisiana and Mississippi. The company, which employs
12,500 people, made a Dollars 482m net profit last year on Dollars 4bn of
revenues. GSU of Beaumont, Texas, is a smaller utility with 579,000
customers in south-east Texas and southern Louisiana. Its 1991 net profit
was Dollars 102m on revenues of Dollars 1.7bn. GSU has 4,500 employees.
The deal may be seen as a resolution of GSU's long-standing woes. The
company invested about Dollars 3bn in the 1980s in a 1,000MW nuclear power
plant in Louisiana, but said yesterday it was only earning a return on about
half the investment because of a lack of customer demand.
Analysts said yesterday the merger seemed promising. But they warned
approval could be lengthy. Entergy said yesterday it would raise the price
of the transaction if it had not been completed by June 1994.
Mr Edwin Lupberger, chairman of Entergy, said the deal would create a more
competitive and efficient company and would lead to fuel-cost savings,
operational advantages and cost efficiencies.
Mr Edward Tirello, an analyst at Smith Barney Harris Upham, said GSU had
faced threats from competition in the past. 'By going with Entergy, a larger
company with a more diverse fuel base, they will be able to lower prices to
keep their industrial customers, such as the petrochemical and oil refining
business,' he said.
Salomon Brothers is advising Entergy. GSU's adviser is Goldman Sachs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
