FT  09 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs attack banks over Maxwell cash
 -Pensioners say government aid plan inadequate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, NORMA COHEN and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMMERCIAL banks were put under heavy pressure yesterday as MPs on both
sides of the Commons put the onus on them to recognise their moral
obligation to the Maxwell pensioners.
The government also faced unease from both Labour and Tory MPs when Mr Peter
Lilley, social security secretary, was unable to give an assurance that the
government's measures would mean that all pensioners would continue to
receive a full pension indefinitely.
That concern was echoed by a number of pensioners in Robert Maxwell's
company pension schemes, who hailed the government's announcement of an
interim aid package, but said that it fell far short of what was needed.
In the Commons, Mr Lilley defended the offer as a move to tackle 'a
particularly acute short-term pressure which is unique to this case'.
Mr Richard Page, the Tory co-chairman of the all-party group of MPs
campaigning on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners, and other backbenchers,
urged Mr Lilley to keep up the pressure on the banks.
Other MPs from both sides of the Commons expressed anger at the position of
members of the Maxwell family.
Mr Frank Field, Labour co-chairman of the all-party group and chairman of
the cross-party social security committee in the last parliament, welcomed
Mr Lilley's enthusiasm 'for shaking warmly by the throat the banks,
financial institutions, companies, individuals and members of the Maxwell
family who have done so well out of the Maxwell years, in order to get
contributions to rebuild the pension funds'.
National Westminster Bank, one of the banks that holds shares claimed by the
Maxwell pension funds, said it had been considering a voluntary fund
launched by government and the City as a way of helping Maxwell pensioners
without admitting liability for their losses.
It added, however, that it had to put the interests of its shareholders
first and therefore could not transfer to the pension funds shares in Teva,
an Israeli pharmaceutical company, which are claimed by the funds.
They are also being claimed by the administrator of the Robert Maxwell
Group, the parent of the Maxwell private interests, as well as by the
liquidator of Bishopsgate Investment Management, trustee of the pension
funds.
Mr Kenneth Trench, chairman of the Maxwell Pensioners Action Group, said he
was confident that banks and financial institutions holding some Pounds 217m
in securities belonging to the pension funds would return those assets.
'I'm taking a bet that the banks will return the Pounds 217m,' he said,
adding that even then pensioners would still need more than Pounds 200m to
meet all obligations.
He was critical that the government's measures appeared to exclude all those
who were not pensioners when the schemes collapsed but have retired since.
'A 64-year-old with 30 years' service who retires tomorrow will not be
helped,' Mr Trench said.
The scope of the measures will be tested by MPs today in the Commons debate.
Mr Field will be among those to press Mr Lilley for an assurance that if the
trustees say that the Pounds 2.5m announced yesterday is inadequate, then
the government will not end the scheme without making a further statement to
MPs.
</TEXT>
