<DATE>920609
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: A crusade into Medieval law -
Review of pension fund regulation welcomed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE pensions industry, thriving under a loose patchwork of laws and
practices, faces a radical overhaul after yesterday's announcement of a
wide-ranging government review.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, said that an independent
commission, headed by Professor Roy Goode QC of Oxford University, would
study the framework of pensions legislation and make recommendations within
12 months.
The National Association of Pension Funds, the trade association that has
offered cautious endorsement of some elements of pension fund reform, said
it welcomed the commission.
The review is to follow closely a report from the cross-party Commons select
committee on social security, issued in early March, which recommended
sweeping changes to the trust law that has been the basis of pension fund
operation since the 1920s. The committee had concluded that trust law,
designed in the Middle Ages to protect the estates of knights on crusade,
may be inadequate in that it does not take into account that the interests
of trustees may be at odds with those of beneficiaries.
It also urged requirements for scheme members to be widely represented on
pension boards and a number of custodial practices designed to frustrate the
designs of larcenous pension fund managers hoping to secure scheme assets
for their own benefit.
Most significantly, Mr Lilley has specifically ordered that the commission
is to study what is acknowledged to be the thorniest issue facing the
industry: the ownership of assets. Many employers have seized upon the
existence of surpluses in recent years as an opportunity to take a
'contributions holiday', cutting their annual expenses significantly by
allowing high investment returns built up in prior years to cover employer
contributions for the future.
Depending on the wording of trust deeds, employers may legally withdraw huge
sums from their own pension schemes without sharing those benefits with
employees.
Indeed, it emerged during the select committee hearings that Robert Maxwell
was able to strip more out of the pension fund surpluses of companies he
acquired than he paid for them in the first place.
Pensions industry professionals say pension-fund reform cannot be considered
separately from ownership of assets. Thus far, there is no statutory answer
to the question, they say, but judgments about the best way to require the
administration of schemes is clearly dependent upon whom one believes they
belong to.
Meanwhile, it is expected that the new commission will have to address the
question of a compensation scheme for pensioners who may be affected by
future fund collapses. While Mr Lilley did not single out the construction
of a compensation scheme as part of the commission's remit, the select
committee specifically urged that one be studied.
Already the proposal is causing controversy within the industry, partly
because large, well run schemes have balked at the idea of paying to bail
out weaker ones.
Mr Tom Ross, partner at actuaries Clay and Partners and chairman of an NAPF
subcommittee studying a compensation scheme, said that the experience of the
US and other foreign pension-fund safety nets in other countries showed that
no scheme would work unless its participants were required to reduce their
own risks.
'My own view is that if a pension scheme compensation fund were set up, you
cannot give people a blank cheque,' he said. However, it was precisely those
schemes which were most reluctant to adopt certain minimum standards that
were most likely to need a scheme, he added.
'My own view is that no scheme will work unless it is compulsory.
'But none of these issues - compensation, ownership of assets, safety of
funds - can be considered on its own. They are all connected and must be
considered together.'
Industry professionals note that every other aspect of investment - life
insurance, bank and building society deposits, unit trusts and other retail
financial investments - are covered by a compensation scheme of some sort.
Pension-fund experts say that the construction of a compensation scheme
might well require amendments to trust law because trustees are required to
use assets solely for the benefit of members. Thus schemes would have to
argue that the construction of a scheme was in members' best interests
before they could be allowed to contribute to it.
Industry sources say that some months ago, the Department of Social Security
broached the question of compensation for the Maxwell company pensioners
with the industry and sought legal advice on the matter. The DSS dropped the
matter after learning that trustees were barred from any such payments.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
