<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Trade and Industry adopted its normal practice with
investigations yesterday by appointing two experts to examine Mirror Group
Newspapers - a lawyer and an accountant.
Mr John Laugharne Thomas QC, aged 44, who is based at 4 Essex Court in the
Temple, London, specialises in a wide range of commercial and international
law in one of the leading commercial sets, or practices.
Mr Thomas was called to the Bar in 1969. He was appointed a Queen's Counsel
in 1984, and in 1987 became a recorder on the Wales and Chester circuit.
He has been a visiting faculty fellow in maritime law at the University of
Southampton for the past two academic years.
Mr Raymond Turner, aged 56, a senior partner with Neville Russell, a firm of
accountants with many insurance-sector clients, was previously part of the
team investigating BOM Holdings Group, a DTI probe launched in February 1990
and which reported earlier this year.
He has also previously worked on a number of confidential DTI
investigations.
His other appointments have included being liquidator to CR Driver, a small
insurance underwriting firm closely linked with London United Investments,
the insurance group that collapsed in May 1990.
