<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont rules out early City reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REGULATION of financial services will remain unchanged as a result of the
Treasury's new responsibilities for the industry, Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, said last night.
On the day he took over responsibilities previously held by the Department
of Trade and Industry, Mr Lamont made clear that he did not envisage an
early shake-up in the City's system of self-regulation.
Speculation about possible reforms had been encouraged by the appointment of
Mr Anthony Nelson as economic secretary to the Treasury. Before he became a
minister he was a critic of the City 'club' and a proponent of extra powers
for the Securities and Investments Board.
At the minimum, yesterday's statement suggests that there will be no
immediate move towards giving the Bank of England a more direct role in
overseeing the City's investment markets.
Mr Lamont said financial services had become increasingly closely linked in
the UK and overseas, justifying the bringing together of responsibilities
into a single department.
'No changes are proposed in the way financial services are regulated as a
result of the transfer,' he said in a Commons written answer.
The transfer involved the functions and staff of the DTI's financial
services division. They covered policy, legislation and the overseeing of
regulation in the areas of investment business, collective investment
schemes, the issue of securities to the public and investor protection.
The Treasury will now have responsibility for the regulatory system set up
under the 1986 Financial Services Act, including overseeing SIB.
The DTI will continue to have responsibility for company law and for
investigations under the financial services, insolvency and companies acts.
It will retain responsibility for the insurance industry.
</TEXT>
