<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / TV network contract won
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MULTI-million-pound contract for a microwave network linking the studios
of Westcountry Television, the new broadcaster for south-west England, will
be awarded today to National Transcommunications.
The Westcountry network will be the first such television system to be
independent of BT, which has been involved in the television industry since
the 1930s.
National Transcomm, formed from the engineering division of the old
Independent Broadcasting Authority, will be installing a network that will
not only link studios in the region but carry virtually all Westcountry's
internal communications and data links.
The deal is a small example of plans to modernise the UK's broadcasting
infrastructure and provide digital networks.
Earlier this year BT signed a Pounds 50m contract over 10 years for an
advanced digital network for Channel 4 - a network that will allow the
channel to broadcast different adver-tisements simultaneously in six
regional TV areas.
BT's broadcast and visual services division has started negotiating with the
main ITV companies and the BBC to provide them with modern digital
communications. Investment of about Pounds 100m is required.
BT has warned the broadcasters that the existing system, dating from the
1960s, cannot be sustained after 1994 as faults continue to increase.
'Some of the switches need oilcans,' said Mr Steve Maine, director of BT
broadcast and visual services.
</TEXT>
