<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / Tenders to run council housing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSING associations and private-sector companies are to be invited to
tender for the management of 4m council homes under plans announced
yesterday by Sir George Young, the housing minister.
Launching a green paper setting out the government's proposals, Sir George
told a London conference on housing management that the extension of
contracting-out to council housing would help tenants getting a bad deal.
He said: 'There are too many estates where management breakdown is evident,
with empty properties boarded up for long periods or taken over by
squatters.'
Compulsory competitive tendering would encourage decentralisation and tenant
involvement in management, the minister said.
The plans were attacked by Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local-government
spokesman, as 'pure party-political dogma'. He said tenants would suffer
while some private companies made 'a killing'.
The government published a report on the scope for competitive tendering in
housing management, commissioned from consultants last year. It said that
competition would improve efficiency by focusing on cost accounting and
quality assessment.
The consultants recommended, however, that tendering for housing management
should be introduced gradually, to allow councils to develop the necessary
systems.
Competing for quality in housing. Department of the Environment, 2 Marsham
Street, London SW1P 3EB. Free.
The scope for competitive tendering of housing management. HMSO. Pounds
7.50.
Editorial comment, Page 18
</TEXT>
