<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / Exports lead textile recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXPORTS are leading a patchy recovery in the textiles and clothing
industries, according to the sector's trade association.
In its latest quarterly report, the Apparel, Knitting and Textiles Alliance
(AKT) found that textile and clothing exports rose 9 per cent to Pounds
1.1bn in the first quarter of this year, compared with that period last
year. Imports edged 2 per cent higher to Pounds 2.1bn.
Domestic sales 'remained stagnant despite extensive price cutting', the AKT
said. Retailers continued a cautious approach to ordering, which encouraged
the manufacturers' drive for exports.
Mr Colin Purvis, AKT director, said: 'We are getting better at exporting,
especially to markets in southern Europe.'
Clothing exports grew 10 per cent to Pounds 445m, helped by a sharp rise in
sales to the Commonwealth of Independent States, albeit from a low level.
The largest export market remains Ireland, with Germany and France close
behind.
Textile and clothing imports from the rest of the European Community rose by
16 per cent, partly counterbalanced by a 7 per cent fall in imports from the
US.
The AKT has not published employment levels this quarter because government
estimates are 'unreliable'. Mr Purvis said Department of Employment figures
overestimated employment in the industry.
</TEXT>
