FT  09 JUN 92 / BA faces strikes in cabin crew pay row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AIRWAYS services in the UK and Europe face disruption after cabin
crew on short-haul flights voted to strike over pay cuts for employees in UK
regions.
The TGWU general workers' union said a ballot among 2,900 cabin crew members
had produced a two-to-one majority for strike action.
BA's proposals would mean cuts of Pounds 2,000 for employees operating
European and UK routes from Birmingham and Manchester who the company says
earn Pounds 12,000 a year.
Next year they would receive a pay rise only if inflation was above 4 per
cent. In addition they would lose holiday pay supplements.
BA said pilots and ground staff had agreed to similar proposals. The effects
of the cuts would be softened by such methods as phasing them in over an
18-month period.
Mr George Ryde, TGWU national secretary, said cabin crew would not tolerate
wage cuts while Lord King, BA chairman, and other BA bosses were 'handing
each other huge increases', and the compnay was reporting its second-highest
profits.
The TGWU would not say how many people voted in the ballot. BA managers
believe that might signify a low turnout, especially among London cabin
crew.
</TEXT>
