<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / Complaints body says coverage of royalty 'odious'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Press Complaints Commission attacked newspaper coverage of the
apparently strained marriage of the Prince and Princess of Wales as 'odious'
yesterday and warned that it threatened the future of press self-regulation.
Further criticism of newspapers came from Dr George Carey, the archbishop of
Canterbury, who said: 'The current speculation about intimate personal
matters has exceeded the boundaries which should be observed in a society
claiming to respect basic human values.'
Speculation over the state of the royal marriage has filled many newspapers
since Friday, when the front page of the Daily Mail claimed that the
Princess had attempted suicide during the 1980s.
The story was based on a biography of the Princess to be published in the US
next month. Other newspapers followed with detailed allegations from a rival
biography, serialised in The Sunday Times.
The Press Complaints Commission described some reports as 'an odious
exhibition of journalists dabbling their fingers in the stuff of other
people's souls in a manner which adds nothing to legitimate public interest
in the situation of the heir to the throne'.
It added: 'The state of the marriage has been put into the public domain in
part at least by the outward behaviour of the spouses and it is therefore a
legitimate subject within the public interest for report and comment by the
press.'
But it said that frequently the manner and tone of the reports was without
doubt in breach of the newspapers' code of practice.
Mr David Mellor, national heritage minister, welcomed the commission's
statement and said the government would take its views into account in the
government's review of press self-regulation at the end of this month.
</TEXT>
