<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 92 / DTI launches inquiry into Mirror group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WIDE-RANGING inquiry into the tangled affairs of Mirror Group Newspapers,
the heart of the late Robert Maxwell's publishing empire, was launched
yesterday by the Department of Trade and Industry.
The announcement of the inquiry by Mr Michael Heseltine, secretary of state
for trade and industry, more than seven months after Mr Maxwell's death
could cause greater uncertainty for the newspaper group, which includes the
Daily Mirror, Sunday Mirror and The People.
It could also delay further the sale of the majority stake in the group
which is now, in effect, controlled by a group of banks led by National
Westminster.
The DTI inspectors, Mr John Laugharne Thomas QC and accountant Mr Raymond
Thomas Turner, have been asked to investigate 'the affairs and membership'
of MGN and, in particular, the flotation in April last year of 49 per cent
of the company's shares which raised Pounds 245.5m.
A total of 196.39m shares were offered, with Samuel Montagu, the merchant
bank, offering 114m in the UK. Apart from employees' stakes, more than 78m
shares were offered to institutional shareholders outside the UK by Salomon
Brothers International.
One of the key issues to be investigated will be whether the assurances
given at the time by the company and its advisers that there would be a
'ring fence' separating MGN from other Maxwell interests were credible.
Other issues are likely to include statements made in the flotation document
about the state of the MGN pension funds and the company's property leasing
arrangements.
Yesterday's government announcement revived ironic memories of a previous
DTI inspectors' report in 1971 which Robert Maxwell complained about for the
rest of his life.
That report concluded that Mr Maxwell had shown 'reckless and unjustified
optimism' in making statements he must have known to be untrue. 'We regret
having to conclude that notwithstanding Mr Maxwell's acknowledged abilities
and energy, he is not in our opinion a person who can be relied on to
exercise proper stewardship of a publicly-quoted company,' it said.
The appointment of the inspectors yesterday came as Maxwell pensioners
marched to the House of Commons to protest against the more than Pounds 400m
missing from their pension funds. The issue is due to be debated today in
parliament.
Some in the City expressed surprise at the decision to set up an inquiry so
many months after the scandal first broke. 'This owes more to the
government's political timetable than the position of the company,' one
banker said.
Ministers said privately the decision had been taken because the inquiries
of the Serious Fraud Office were going in a different direction. Ministers
were keen that matters of corporate governance be properly explored.
Key witnesses for the inspectors who have been appointed under sections
432(2) and 442 of the Companies Act 1985 will be senior executives of Samuel
Montagu and Smith New Court, brokers for the flotation. Sir Michael
Richardson, Smith New Court chairman, declined to comment. Samuel Montagu
said it would co-operate fully.
The news of the inquiry comes at a particularly difficult time for MGN. The
company is in the final stages of negotiating a Pounds 250m two-year finance
facility designed to meet its needs until its future has been determined.
Full accounts were expected to be published at the end of this month in
advance of a relisting of its shares, suspended since late last year.
It is unclear whether the relisting will now be held up, although specialist
advisers to the company said a delay was far from inevitable.
A lot of the basic work has already been done which should help the DTI
inspectors.
At the beginning of this year the directors of MGN commissioned consultants
Ernst &amp; Young to carry out a full study.
MGN last night declined to comment other than to say it welcomed the
decision to hold an inquiry and would co-operate fully with the DTI
inspectors.
